In 2019, the University of North Carolina Wilmington received a $394,606.00 NSF ITEST grant titled "Virtual Access to STEM Careers (VASC)." VASC is a technology rich, inquiry and problem-based curriculum designed to expose and stimulate student interest in marine, environmental, computer, and geological sciences. The VASC project focused on grades three through five and builds academic momentum at the intermediate level to prepare students for STEM opportunities later in middle school and high school. The VASC project is aligned to Next Generation Science Standards and Common Core State Standards for North Carolina. VASC immerses students in rigorous, high-interest learning modules where students are introduced and take on the roles and responsibilities of different STEM occupations. 
The goals of the VASC project are
1.   The development of Immersive Virtual Environments using input from conservationists and the educational team; 


2.    The development of a science/math curriculum that is accessible to students at-risk for academic failure and from diverse locations and backgrounds (e.g., poverty, disability, etc.); 


3.    The development of a curriculum that sparks interest in pursuing a STEM career in marine, environmental, geological, and computer sciences; 


4.    The creation and implementation of trainings on Immersive Virtual Environments for students; and 


5.    The assessment of technology using a multiple baseline design to determine effectiveness when compared to traditional hands-on STEM learning. 


The VASC application and curriculum was tested in three different informal and formal education settings and with over 200 underrepresented and underpriveleged students. During the tenure of this project we have adressed the five goals of the Virtual Access to STEM Careers project. Conservationist, career specialist and educational experts in all the areas used in VASC system were members of the development team and were consulted at every step during the implementation of this project. The data from the interactions and assessments with students and teachers revealed an increased level of engagement and interest in STEM. The final version of the VASC project during the tenure of this project has been diseminated to the Bald Head Island Conservancy for use in summer camps, demonstrations and tour guides. This project led to many more collaborators in the Wilmington, NC region and is helping continue the extension of the VASC project.

